In Fig. 5
                        , XPS is applied to analyze the element composition and content of F/N-G-CDs, F/N-Y-CDs and F/N-O-CDs. Fig. 5 (a,f,k) demonstrate that C 1s, O 1s, N 1s, F 1s and Na 1s elements existed on the carbonaceous structure of tricolor F/N-CDs. Fig. 5 (ãe) is the high resolution full‐survey, C 1s, O 1s, N 1s and Na 1s XPS spectra of F/N-G-CDs. In Fig. 5 (b), the C 1s spectra centering at 284.13 eV can be deconvoluted into four characteristic peaks at 284.04 eV, 284.7 eV, 285.80eV and 287.60 eV which are indexed to the C-O/C-N, C-H, C=O and C-F groups. On the other side, the characteristic peak of carboxyl carbon (O-C=O) should be originated from modified F/N-CDs [34]. In Fig. 5 (c), the O 1s region with a central binding energy of 531.01 eV can be divided into three characteristic peaks of 530.56 eV, 532.35 eV and 535.30, corresponding to C=O, O-H/C-O and O-Na groups, respectively [35]. As Fig. 5 (d) shows, the binding energy centering at 398.03 eV is attributed to N 1s which is divided into two peaks of C-N (397.9 eV) and N-H (398.6 eV) [36]. As can be seen from Fig. 5 (e), the Na 1s spectrum shows a peak at 1070.27 eV which can be ascribed to Na-O. According to the high resolution XPS spectra, the tricolor F/N-CDs have the same elemental composition and almost the same binding energy, but their element content are different (Table 1
                        ). With the increase of NaOH, the proportion of C and N elements gradually decreases, and the content of O and F gradually increases, successfully introducing F and N surface defects.
